## What this is

This deployment is a self-hosted **agency operating system**. Four subsystems
boot together and stay wired:

1. **This Claude-side OS** ŌĆö the file you are reading, the MCP server, the
   SessionStart hooks, and the memory seed.
2. **Directus + the `os_*` schema** ŌĆö the shared-state bus (tasks, sprints,
   projects, releases, repositories) that a human and the agent fleet both read
   and write. This is the single source of truth for work.
3. **A local RAG knowledge engine** ŌĆö semantic search over your docs; Claude is
   the only LLM, no external inference.
4. **The portal** ŌĆö the human observability surface over the same data.

You (Claude) reach the shared bus through the **`elk-os-cms` MCP server**, which
is pointed at this deployment's own Directus at `{{DIRECTUS_URL}}`.

## 1. Work lands on the `os_tasks` board ŌĆö always

The `os_tasks` collection in Directus is the shared substrate. The human watches
it in the portal; the agent fleet reads and writes it over MCP. **If a session
produces a follow-up that is required but not finished by the time the session
ends, write it to `os_tasks` ŌĆö never leave it floating in chat.** Tasks in chat
get forgotten between sessions; tasks on the board survive and show up for the
human.

When creating a task, set at minimum:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| `name` | Short imperative title |
| `description` | Markdown: context, what's done, what's left, file refs |
| `status` | `pending` if not started, `in_progress` mid-work, `completed` only if confirmed done |
| `priority` | `P0`/`P1`/`P2`/`P3` (default `P2`) |

Use the MCP `items` tool (`read`/`create`/`update`/`delete` on `os_tasks`) for
all board operations. Call the MCP `system-prompt` tool first in a session to
learn the live schema before writing.

## 2. Never paste live tokens or secrets into chat

Secrets live only in the deployment `.env` (gitignored) and reach a session
through the environment ŌĆö the MCP server reads `${DIRECTUS_ADMIN_TOKEN}` from the
shell, never from a committed file. If a secret lands in chat, treat it as
compromised and rotate it before the session ends.

## 3. Branching: one trunk = production

One trunk per repo, and the **GitHub default branch MUST be the branch that
deploys to production** (`main`). All work flows through short-lived branches
(`feat/ŌĆ”`, `fix/ŌĆ”`, `chore/ŌĆ”`) off that trunk and squash-merges back. Never
keep a second long-lived mainline (`working`, `develop`) ŌĆö PRs silently merge
into the wrong branch and ship nothing. Confirm a PR's base is the trunk before
merging.

## 4. Versioning is automated ŌĆö never hand-bump

Every repo follows **semver** and the version is bumped automatically from
**Conventional Commit** messages (`feat:` ŌåÆ minor, `fix:`/`perf:` ŌåÆ patch,
`feat!:`/`BREAKING CHANGE` ŌåÆ major) by release automation on merge to trunk. Do
not edit `version` in `package.json` by hand. Because the bump is derived from
commit messages, **every PR title / squash commit must be a valid Conventional
Commit** ŌĆö this is load-bearing, not just style.

## 5. Document what ships (releases)

When a meaningful batch ships, record it as a **release** with a grouped
markdown changelog (Added / Changed / Fixed / Security / Breaking). The
`releases` collection surfaces this in the portal; don't let shipped work go
undocumented.

## 6. Closing a piece of work

When a non-trivial task is done, close the loop in both places:
1. update its `os_tasks` row (`status`, completion notes) so the human sees it;
2. if the session learned something durable and non-obvious, record it in
   `.claude/memory/` and add a one-line pointer to `.claude/memory/MEMORY.md`.

That two-place close is what makes the human <-> agent loop legible from either side.

